<TITLE> 3 submit mercy petitions: official </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 9 (bdnews24.com) - A top jail official has said three of the five former army officers convicted and condemned to death for the 1975 murder of Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman have sought clemency from the president. "Three of the five convicts have submitted mercy petitions," a deputy inspector general of prisons told bdnews24.com, but he did not reveal the names. He said prison authorities would give details in a press briefing later in the day. The Supreme Court in a long-awaited judgement, on Nov 19 last year, rejected appeals of five convicted killers, upholding their death sentences. On Jan 3, Dhaka district and sessions judge sent the signed death warrants of the fiveBazlul Huda, Mohiuddin Ahmed, Syed Faruque Rahman, Sultan Shahriyar Rashid Khan and AKM Mohiuddinto the Dhaka Central Jail. The condemned men had 7 days from receiving the death warrants to seek clemency, according to law. Prison authorities have said they are preparing for execution of the judgement. Sentences must legally be executed between 21 and 28 days
